I examined the code for occurrences of for statements relevant to MISRA C 2023 Rule 14.2. There is a single for loop:

for (i = 0; i < (size_t) res; i++)
  if (! isprint ((unsigned char) fn[i]))
    fn[i] = '_';

This loop meets the rule clauses:
- First clause: initializes the loop counter (i = 0) — allowed.
- Second clause: uses the loop counter and the variable res. The condition has no persistent side effects, and res is not modified inside the loop body. Additionally, res was previously checked to be > 0 and < sizeof(fn), preventing negative or out-of-range iterations.
- Third clause: i++ modifies only the loop counter.
- There is only one loop counter (i), and i is not modified within the loop body. The loop body calls isprint and modifies fn[i]; neither modifies the loop counter or res.

No other for statements or constructs that would fall under Rule 14.2 were found in the function. Therefore there are no code fragments that require further investigation for Rule 14.2 compliance.
